title: VESA mount monitor on wall
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
One of the things I love about 3d printing is that it actually creates a whole community without which the boundries of 3d printing would be severely limited. Recycling other peoples ideas and things, not only greatly reduces the time needed to fullfill your needs , but it also creates a basic toolbox where you dont need to design everything from scratch My idea was to mount my TFT monitor on the wall and also to put in two rails (similar to the X-axis of a 3d printer) in order to be moved parallel to my bench. So I got a VESA mount from this thing
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:213447 and the Z bar clamp from Mendel90 (adjusted for 12mm bars) and I designed a carriage you can screw the monitor vesa mount (stealing the linear bearing trap also from mendel90)
and Voila!
now my monitor is attached on the wall moving a meter to the left and right I also included the freecad file for anyone who wnats to adapt it to her own needs.

you just print the parts.   
VESA mount is for both 7cm and 10cm VESA variety .  
the Carriage is designed to be used with 12mm hollow bars (I use aluminum) instead of linear bearings, as I believe the use of linear bearings is an overkill for the application.  
zipties secure the bars on the carriage :)

comments.text: I have printed 2 of these now for my LCDs and just now gave you kudos on Google+.  Really excellent thing.

title: IDE FilaSense Filament Runout Sensor f. MakerBot Replicator 2 & 2X

description.text:
The IDE FilaSense Filament Runout Sensor prevents failed / incomplete prints, caused by filament runout. When the sensor recognizes the end of the filament, it sets your printer to pause (there is a cold- and a warm pause mode, to fit every need). It gives an accustic signal for 10 seconds and after that it sends a discreet beep every 30 seconds. So even if you are out of office you can change the filament when you are back, and you are able to complete the print. Super easy installation and handling. No modifications on the electronics or the firmware and software needed, you only need to plug it in.

You can order it from www.ide-3d.de in the Replicator 2 & 2X section

Here is a video that shows the function:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bF7hWRzKcZ4

How to install it:
https://www.youtube.com/edit?o=U&video_id=JNW5M_GXBNI

This is a adjustable OpenSCAD design for mounting both the laser diode and coin battery with standard connector for an external switch. Assembly requires soldering wires and a hot glue gun.

Edit the OpenSCAD file to enter dimensions for the specific laser pointer you are using. These are "d_lamp" and "l_lamp" for diameter and length of the laser pointer. You may need to add a little extra room to fit it properly. Use OpenSCAD to generate your custom STL file.

In the USA you can use a Class IIIa laser diode module for gun sights. These lasers do not exceed 5mW output and designed to not cause eye damage if inadvertently viewed. These are commonly used for laser pointers (presentations and cat torture) and laser gun sights. Don't be outfitting this with a Class IIIR or Class IV laser as someone will get hurt. Do take care never to intentionally point the laser into anyone's eyes. Any respectable CQB Arena should ban you for life for not following basic safety requirements.

The battery is based on a CR2032 size. This fits a common 3v coin battery, but 3.7v li-ion rechargeable also exist and should work better. The holder I use also fits a CR2016. The laser diodes typically work from 2v to 5v and draw 20mA to 30mA. Check the specs for your laser module to make sure it fits into these ranges. Output of the laser is typically regulated by the module, not the input voltage.

A 1.25mm 2-pin male connector is fitted into the side for the switch. You may need to adjust the dimensions for your connector's housing. Of course using the connector is optional but makes wiring for the switch easier.

You'll need two 4x30mm screws and matching nuts to attach the laser mount to your picatinny rail.

This was originally based on https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:641947 for the mount and lamp design.

The momentary switch mount was designed to press fit to the G&G ARP9.

This Christmas ornament is a variation of Ugly Ball 9 with fewer larger holes that are round.  This turns Ugly Ball 12 into a display case in which you can place an object that will be fully enclosed by the ornament's shell.  Just pause your 3D print part way through, drop in the object, and then continue the print.  
My Ugly Ball series is a celebration of Moms everywhere who love their children enough to save the crude things they make in their youth, in this case a papier mache globe ornament that I made at five or six years old for my Mom.  Over forty years later it still goes on the tree every year and has become a family heirloom.  So I give you the Ugly Ball series!  
p.s. I modified this object for the Thigiverse Customizer - try it!  :)

3D print this thing about half or two-thirds of the way complete, pause your print, drop in an object to become trapped inside the Ugly Ball, then continue your 3D print.  The result will be a beautiful display ornament with the contents visible through the array of holes.  
Since this is my most popular design, I decided to modify it to work in the Thingiverse Customizer and I tested it, works great!  Please note that when you change some parameters you may get an unprintable object so just tweak the sliders until it becomes printable again.  This has to do with the parameters that affect the number and size of the holes.

comments.text: I improved the Customization interface so that you can change the amount of reduction (or increase)  of hole size as the rows approach the north and south poles of the sphere.  Also changed the depth of the hole punching cylinder so that it reaches all the way to the center of the sphere to accommodate low hollow values.  Please note that holeSizeScaled, num, and shrinkage all work together so it is easy to make an unprintable object.  If that happens, just pay attention to how these three sliders work together and you'll soon have the Ugly Ball 12 that you like best.  Compile times are about a minute or less for each slider adjust meant, so either be patient or reduce the detail variables to speed up the results.  Try low detail values to get faceted looks.  Enjoy!

description.text:
Hello !

Here is my submission for the Snowflake Challenge. I made a snap-together snowflake using BlocksCAD (see the steps below). Enjoy !

Step 1: Fuse two triangles using a loop. (little tip: to obtain sharp faces, create a very thin torus, then scale it bigger) Step 2: The six branches are each composed of three cubes. Make one and reapeat it using another loop. Step 3: Make the difference of the previous shape minus a long cube, to create the slot. Step 4: Create a linear repetition of the previous shape, using a loop again. Step 5: Create the frame. It is composed of many cube so the blocks are not good-looking...
This is a schedule to tell someone if you are busy or not!

description.text:
My Z Carriages started cracking on my Anycubic I3 so i decided to upgrade them. The LM8LUU bearings are clamped in with set screws and so far they work great.

I moved the motor to the front of the carriage to put the center of the motor weight closer to the Z lead screws to stop twisting.

There is a integrated X Endstop built into the left carriage.

I did not include anything for a Z-Min endstop because i am using a probe and a Z-Max endstop. I hate using the Z-max endstop but the smoothieware overlords are dead set on not letting me use my probe as Z-min.

The right carriage will require springs for the belt tensioner. The springs i designed them for are 9.6mm OD and 27mm length relaxed.

The belt tensioner will require a 16 tooth Idler pulley with a 3mm bore. This also means you need to change the belt drive pulley out to 16 tooth to maintain alignment.

I designed the carriages to use spring loaded anti-backlash nuts. they work well.

If you have any questions please let me know in the comments. if you print them and please let me know how they work.

print_settings.Notes:: You can print with or without the raft, just need to make sure it stays stuck down, as the lowest surface is holding the unit level. You'll need supports but just at the build platform. I used PLA at 100mm speeds with no issues. I'm sure you can print out of PETG as well.

description.text:
I had the circuit board fan in my CR-10 fail after about 2 months of use. I took the unit apart and replaced the fan, but while I was in there I was unimpressed with the units overall cooling, especially given the amount of time its on per day. So of course the maker side of me decided to fix the problem with the machine with the machine!

I printed these as two separate parts that interlock so they would fit on the machine print bed easily. They exactly fit 120mm fans and have the mounting holes as well. I've notched out the area for the 3 wire to come out the back. In my case, I got a small CPU power supply and juice them up from a toggle switch. I placed the front fan blowing up and the rear fan blowing down to maximize air flow thru the unit. You'll need to remove the bottom plate from the unit to allow the air flow from this base design.

The result: MUCH better cooling, which should lead to longer component life.

I've uploaded the STL files, but let me know if you're interested in another file format. I own Solidworks and can export to nearly any file type.

Thanks,
Johnny Mac

Printer:

CR-10

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1 layer thickness

Infill:

25

Notes:

You can print with or without the raft, just need to make sure it stays stuck down, as the lowest surface is holding the unit level. You'll need supports but just at the build platform. I used PLA at 100mm speeds with no issues. I'm sure you can print out of PETG as well.

Solidworks, a tape measure and a pair of digital calipers

I just measured the Cr-10 unit and gave the base clearance. Measured two standard 120mm fans to ensure their fit. Carved out an area for the wires, then drafted and filleted for looks. Finally, I split the model into two pieces and created interlocking tab/slots to snap it together.

This is a randomized fractal (recursive) snowflake implemented in BlocksCAD.

To keep symmetry, I used a simple seeded pseudo-random number generator rather than the built-in generator (though you can set the seed to -1, and then it'll be seeded from the built-in generator, so you'll get different output each time).

The Thingiverse customizer was made by exporting from BlocksCAD to OpenSCAD and moving the variable definitions to the top of the file.

I am attaching an image showing seeds 1-100 so you can choose which one you like. There are many more seeds available, of course (up to around 4 billion).

The BlocksCAD project page is here: https://www.blockscad3d.com/community/projects/68072

For printing, I recommend increasing retraction to minimize whiskers, and then begining the removal from the bed with a razor.

remixed_from.author: rcolyer
remixed_from.title: Ergonomic Door Knob Lever, Fully Parametric

description.text:
This is a customizable adapter to convert a round door knob into a door handle with a lever. It is a remix of my previous design, but adapted to be overall thicker and sturdier, to render 10 times faster, and to work with Customizer.

As before this is a smooth ergonomic design, so depending on your computer it may take a few minutes to render.

The most elegant resulting appearance is obtained if you match the nom_knob_diam variable in the .scad file to within at least 0.3mm of the correct diameter for your door knob. Calipers and good calibration are helpful for this, otherwise you may have to adjust and reprint. You can also try terminating a test print early, and using the first few layers to check your measurement. At the ideal size the nut and bolt sides will clamp together tightly right as it reaches the desired grip on the door knob. If you aren't getting enough grip to your door knob, try adding a very thin strip of poster putty around the door knob before clamping the lever on.

The example stl file is for a 54.9mm diameter door knob, and is designed to be held on with an M5x18 bolt and an M5 nut.

Note: The OpenSCAD file uses my threading library for creating the properly sized recessed bolt and nut holes. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1686322 The customizable version has the dependencies copied and pasted in since Customizer cannot yet load libraries.

comments.text: I printed one at original values and it looks great. There seems to be a problem with what i'm doing, the file, or thingiverse as I can not get the customizer to work. Is has a fault at the bottom "script has timed out". If you have any tips that I could try that would be awesome. Or if you have a .stp/.step file that you could upload. I use fusion 360 and it appears that it doesn't import scad files. Anyways, thanks in advance for any info and keep up the good work, it is a nice looking handle.

description.text:
If you enjoy any of my Things, please sponsor my charity cycle ride to Paris. https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/petethevanstp or text PTVC63 £5 to 70070 (UK number). Expires 1st May 2018. Thanks!

Note 1: Thingiverse has displayed the STL of the board bottom-side towards the viewer. However, it prints like the photo.

Note 2: Print the board at about 15-25% infill (or whatever), but make sure you use 100% infill for the plug and pegs.

This crib board has a storage hole with a screw plug. Four pegs can be stored in the hole for traveling. When you put the pegs in the storage hole, ensure that the heads all point in the same direction. This removes the slight chance that two "feet" could ride up alongside one another and jam in the hole (a very remote chance, but you never know).

Print the pegs at least four in one go. This reduces the chance that the print head will melt the thin shafts. If you have cooling, use that too. Print the pegs head (sphere) side down.

I printed the pegs both ways, but had more success head-down.

The plug fits snugly into the hole and will screw up flush to the board. The slot was designed to take a small coin.

Printer:

Geeetech Aluminium

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1

Infill:

Board 25%, Peg & Plug 100%

Notes:

Use a large brim (at least 10mm) for the pegs. You stand a change then that they won't be knocked over.

Print the pegs in a different colour to the board.

Clean up the brim (obviously) and with a jeweler's screwdriver or similar sharp pointy thing clean up the threads on the plug and threaded hole.

The threads will take a while to clean up so be careful to remove the supports only.

The storage hole is more challenging. I used a combination of a rat-tailed (thin) file and a thin screwdriver to break the supports out. The screwdriver you choose should fit the hole perfectly and then simply insert and break the supports out down to the bottom of the hole. The bottom is halfway down the board between the 3rd and 4th sets of five holes.

I based this on an old wooden crib board my father made for me when I was child.

I used Fusion 360 & CURA.

title: ArduSat - The Arduino CubeSat Satellite (full scale model)

description.text: This is a full scale (moderately simplified) 3D printer-ready copy of the ArduSat, the wildly successful Kickstarter.com satellite for personal space exploration (received $106,330 funding, 3X their original goal!). I am a supporter of the project, and have worked closely with Joel Spark (provided the original stl files) of the ArduSat team to create the first 3D print of this online. My daughter will be doing a week of ArduSat space science in 2013 when this launches (proud Dad). For space science enthusiasts, see the links below for more background on the ArduSat project: http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/575960623/ardusat-your-arduino-experiment-in-space?ref=live https://www.facebook.com/pages/NanoSatisfi/307866409295499 http://www.youtube.com/user/nanosatisfi?feature=watch

MakerBot Replicator was used for this print. I've grouped and modified a couple of the original files to make it easier to print. Specifically, I've positioned the individual computer boards for optimal printing (Use raft/full support on all of them). Also I've grouped the frame elements for a single print. As well, I've designed the frame rods with an end cap on tinkercad.com and included them here. STLs:
ArduSat_FlatFrame (contains top, bottom, 4 vertical beams, and 4 rods)
ArduSat_FrameRod_4 (separate print of 4 rods... if they break on you)
ArduSat_SolarPanel_2
ArduSat_Payload
ArduSat_PowerSystem
ArduSat_FlightComputer
ArduSat_Transceiver
ArduSat_Spectrometer The most difficult part of this print is cleaning all the support material off of each component! Also, I did not included the spacers in the files, as the rods are a little to wide for them. I might work on that and upload a cleaned version of them in the future. As well, I may include all of the solar panels in a single print once I get the original STLs from the ArduSat team. Toy model (a little solid model of the entire ArduSat with all panels on it):
ArduSat_3cmsolid ArduSat_ALL.zip (I've also included a compressed folder with everything) Overall, this takes the better part of a day to print, but the resulting full scale ArduSat model is really a great thing to hold in your hand and cool desk conversation piece. This satellite will be launched in mid 2013, and used by hundreds of supporters all over the world to do unique space science experiments using the Arduino and sensor payload. For space science enthusiasts, see the links below for more background on the project: http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/575960623/ardusat-your-arduino-experiment-in-space?ref=live https://www.facebook.com/pages/NanoSatisfi/307866409295499 http://www.youtube.com/user/nanosatisfi?feature=watch

title: Eve - singular algebraic surface
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Eve, a singular algebraic surface of degree five. This is the set of real points for which 

0.5*x^2 + 2*x*z^2 + 5*y^6 + 15*y^4 + 0.5*z^2 - (15*y^5 + 5*y^3) = 0.

Has two point singularities!

I have provided these files:

  • Eve_thickened_Blocky_R1_fixed.stl -- has the normal vectors fixed, and is thickened for printing.
  • Eve_thickened_Smooth_R1.stl -- the blocky version, ran through the sampler module for bertini_real.
  • eve_raw_blocky_r1.stl -- raw triangulation coming from Bertini_real. Since the program works in arbitrary dimensions, I make no effort to control normals from it -- they don't exist for 4- and higher-dimensional surfaces, but instead a tangent space which is not immediately useful for 3d printing. Hence, the surface was thickened in Blender, before being passed through Microsoft's 3D Builder to fix internal geometry. The raw versions are not directly suitable for 3d printing.
  • eve_raw_smooth_r1.stl -- infinitely thin, but ran through sampler.
  • input -- the Bertini_real input file used to compute it.

This surface was sampled before I implemented cyclenumber > 1 sampling, so the surface is undersampled near critical points and singularities.

Computed with a Numerical Algebraic Geometry program I wrote, called Bertini_real and printed as part of my long-term project to reproduce Herwig Hauser's gallery of algebraic surface ray-traces in my own gallery of 3d prints. The ACM ToMS algorithm number is 976; the major published paper is DOI 10.1145/3056528 with several others preceding. Bertini_real implements the implicit function theorem for algebraic surfaces and curves in any (reasonable) number of variables.

These surfaces are generally challenging to print. Rotate, and use careful support. I use Simplify3D for the manual support placement feature. These surfaces are also very tiny in scale (arbitrary units and math and all) so require significant upsizing.

See also, my Thingiverse collection of algebraic surfaces.

title: Geisha -- singular algebraic surface
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Geisha, a singular algebraic surface of degree four. This is the set of real points for which 

x^2*y*z + x^2*z^2 -(y^3*z + y^3) = 0.

Two singular lines, and two singular points on those lines!

I have provided these files:

  • geisha_thickened.stl -- has the normal vectors fixed, and is thickened for printing.
  • geisha_raw.stl -- raw triangulation coming from Bertini_real. Since the program works in arbitrary dimensions, I make no effort to control normals from it -- they don't exist for 4- and higher-dimensional surfaces, but instead a tangent space which is not immediately useful for 3d printing. Hence, the surface was thickened in Blender, before being passed through Microsoft's 3D Builder to fix internal geometry. The raw versions are not directly suitable for 3d printing.
  • input -- the Bertini_real input file used to compute it.

This surface was sampled before I implemented cyclenumber > 1 sampling, so the surface is undersampled near critical points and singularities.

Computed with a Numerical Algebraic Geometry program I wrote, called Bertini_real and printed as part of my long-term project to reproduce Herwig Hauser's gallery of algebraic surface ray-traces in my own gallery of 3d prints. The ACM ToMS algorithm number is 976; the major published paper is DOI 10.1145/3056528 with several others preceding. Bertini_real implements the implicit function theorem for algebraic surfaces and curves in any (reasonable) number of variables.

These surfaces are generally challenging to print. Rotate, and use careful support. I use Simplify3D for the manual support placement feature. These surfaces are also very tiny in scale (arbitrary units and math and all) so require significant upsizing.

See also, my Thingiverse collection of algebraic surfaces.

description.text:

Update 04 Jan '18 - New shape cooling tubes (v3) for v.1 effector

Until recently I've used an E3d V6 with this effector https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2361081. Changing to Chimera it meant I couldn't use a Piezo probe and so I had to make a different one.
This one has the same 64mm spacing and Magnetic arms but it's using a 50x15mm Blower and Escher's IR Differential Probe. The cooling air travels from the blower to each nozzle inside the hollow frame and end tubes. That makes for a very light and compact effector.

  • the silicone socks will not fit easily. I had to cut a bit from each one in such way it will still hook fine on all sides

  • see that cooling tubes are not touching the silicone socks. They are close, run the blower at least 20% when heater is on

Enjoy :-)

author: MakinBug

print_settings.Notes:: Leg extenders: 30 %

title: YALE (Yet Another Lack-Table Enclosure)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The idea
Depending on the brand of the printer you bought, the noise can be quiet irritating. As a tinkerer the sound of a 3D-printer is a charm, but lets face it: does everybody in the house thinks the same. Same goes also with the smell, when one starts to print other stuff then PLA.

Therefore I would like to have a enclosure for my 3D-printer:

  • Based on a Ikea Lack table (costs around €5.00 here);
  • Plexiglass all around, supported thickness 3 mm to 8 mm (as I didn't know on beforehand what material I could get my hands on);
  • Sleek design: no visible mounting on the outside of the enclosure, all wires for ventilation and LED-lightning inside the legs of the table;

But there are already tons of enclosures on Thingiverse
Why re-invent the wheel. First of all, I would like to get myself familiarized with designing parts with Fusion 360. Secondly, I'm really fond of the color red. The only better thing than the color red is the combination of the color red with black.

Because the printer is taller than the height of the Lack table, the legs have to be extended. Instead of extending the legs only on one side, I would like to have the legs extended on both side equally. And also add some way to fix the plexiglass sheets as well.

Leg extenders
The leg extenders are placed on both top and bottom of the legs. There are three leg extenders:

  1. leg extenders with two fixed walls (you'll need 4 of these);
  2. leg extenders with one fixed wall and door stop on the other side (you'll need 2 of these). In the door stop there is a recess for a small Neodium magnet with a diameter of 5 mm and a thickness of 2 mm;
  3. leg extenders with one fixed wall and mounting for the hinges of the door (you'll need 2 of these). TODO: this part is still to be designed

The leg extenders are mounted on the table with 3 screws and a 7 mm hexagon head wood screw. The 2 screws on the outside should be 4x12 mm. The one inside the leg should be 3.5x35 mm.

Hidden leg mounts
The leg extenders are mounted on the legs with 2 3.5x35mm screws and a 7 mm hexagon head wood screw. On one side of the leg there is already a mounting hole for the hexagon head wood screw, on the other side a hole should be pre-drilled in the leg.

The legs of the Ikea Lack table are everything but square and 50x50 mm. The accuracyof the leg is enough for an average piece of furniture, but for a sleek enclosure this will make nasty visible lines. Therefore, to mount the hidden leg mount a fixture is included. The notch on the corner will be the outside corner of the leg later on: using the fixture ensures the leg extender on being flush with the outside of the leg.

There are four holes for screws in the mount. This is a little overkill to mount the leg, as the screws only prevent rotation of the mount. I have used some of the holes to put through electricity wires (the legs are hollow). I bored through the top and bottom wood with a 5 mm drill. With a solid rod one can pull the electricity wire through.

Nuts

All parts use M4 nuts for mounting. Using a long bolt and a torch I heated the nuts and pressed them in the holes. Alternatively a solder iron can be used to heat up the nut.

The holes are slightly to small for the nuts, so a good bond is obtained.

title: SBase TFT32 screen housing with 2020 mount

description.text:
I bought the MKS SBase V1.3 board with the TFT32 screen. I designed a housing for the screen and a mount to fit it to 2020 extrusions, or in my case 2040. It leaves access to the USB port of the screen and the DS card reader, none of which I use. It's not a thing of beauty, but it is usefull. In the pictures you can see the surfaces aren't all closed properly as I use very little infill.

To mount it to the 2020 I used two M4x16 bolts and two hammer nuts. The part locks the hammer nuts in place, I find that easy.

To fit the screens, I used a lot of left over weird screws, you are supposed to use four M3x6 bolts with a small washer under the bolt head.

To close the assembly I used two M4x10 bolts with countersunk heads, you should use four. I will do so when the stored open again, and also buy some M3x6...

I might add some better pics later, it's dark now. But I think you get the idea.

The little beeper on the back of the board did not get it's own hole for the sound to exit. I think it is way too loud anyway, the housing mutes it a bit which I like. I've added the FreeCAD files, feel free to make a nice change to this or any other part if you like.

[EDIT Dec 26th, 2017] I've printed a new housing at 20% infill. Takes a little longer but the result is better. The holes holding the bolts are more strong.[/EDIT]

title: Lithophane Lamp v3
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Update

I have released a base that can now support G9 LED Bulbs. Please make sure you use a LED bulb as they generate the least heat. I have yet to print this version but I am confident it will fit fine.

Please make sure to read the tip section. There is good information there to help you put this together.

Version 4 is finished. I will plan on releasing it once I have printed it out and tested it. It may take 2-3 weeks for me to do... Or less as I need to get a valentines gift for my wife made...

Description

Lithophane are great gifts to give to family and friends. They are a great way to show meaningful pictures to everyone in a clever way. When unlit, you can barely see the pictures hidden in the plastic, but with some background light, those images pop out and convoy sentimental pictures that have been chosen. I wanted to design something that not only showed those pictures, but that also looked good as well when not lit.

This is the 3rd iteration of my design. I have another iteration which I am working on that will be released in a while.

Information

The box is meant to hold lithophane pictures of 75mm x 75mm x 3mm.
There is a 2mm border added to hold the pictures in place. I have posted pictures of the settings needed. The site used to create the lithophanes is..
http://3dp.rocks/lithophane/
Please use the settings I have provided as they are a best fit.
Overall, the default tolerance added to the box is 0.4mm. This allows stuff to fit nicely and can help assembly parts with minor defects. They should slide in smoothly and be taken out smoothly with the tolerances added in there. Please do not force the lithophanes in the box, you do not want to break off the posts. If you are seeing fit issues, shave off some of the sides with a knife as there can be excess material on the sides. If not, you may have to reprint the lithospheres a tad bit thinner/smaller

I have provided a bit of a space in the hole on the lid where the posts fit in. This is so you may add glue in the hole to permanently seal it in place. You do not have to glue it in if you don't want. The one I made fits nicely and holds the lid in place.

Tips

When you are getting ready to solder everything, I suggest adding flux to the LED strip pads before you tape them to the walls. This will help you later on when you need to solder the wires in place.

You do not have to tape the LED strips to the walls if you do not want to. They will work just as fine on the base. The LED on the walls help illuminate the lithophanes better tho.

You do not have to use LED strips if you don't want to. Circular LED rings work just as fine as well.Glue or tape it to the bottom and you are set.

Make sure to shave off excess materials off your lithophanes. Since the base is normally squished, you will have a small edge sticking out, just cut it off with a knife or a razor. Just be careful cutting off the excess material.

Supplies Used

5.5 x 2.1mm Barrel Power Female DC Power Cable Jake Adapter Connector Plug 12V
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01IBFNMEQ/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

LED Flexible Light Strip, 12V
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00HSF65MC/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

DC12V 1A UL-Listed Switching Power Supply Adapter
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00FEOB4EI/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

22 Gage wire
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00J4HI746/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

These are the stuff I used to make these. You do not have to use them. I only posted these to show you the type of supplies you will need.

Suggestions

If you have any suggestions or would like me to revise something for you, please let me know so I can work on it. I do need dimensions tho so I can change some things around. I won't be doing them all, but if it's a pretty common suggestion, I will be happy to upload a new version.

comments.text: It is best to print lithophanes standing, not flat. You get greater detail. I have tried printing lithophanes standing up with a brim but for some reason my brim curls if I am not there to push it down with a putty knife so I decided to use a raft but I had to change the air gap (if it is a big print) from .3 to 0 so the lithophane sticks to the raft good. The only issue doing this is that the lithophane sticks too good to the raft and will break if you are not careful. I use the wire cutter that came with my 3d printer and cut the raft off carefully. Make sure you print at slow speeds 45mms and I drop the travel speed to 90mms. Also, if your lithophane is not for a box/picture frame then you can add a stand to it on the 3dp.rocks program. Make sure your resolution/layer height is set correct. My printer has a .4mm nozzle so I print lithophanes at .4mm intervals. For instance, for a good detail print I would print at a layer height of .16, if I want a faster print I would set it to .2 or .24. I am no expert and have only been printing for a year but these settings have worked wonders for me. Hope this helps and I will be printing this thing in the next day or 2  to add to my collection.
comments.author: Dalt3r

comments.text: I would add to deathwarden's comment by suggesting that you orient the lithophane's viewing surface on the same axis as your printer's most accurate axis.  In my case, with a CR-10S, that is the X axis.  The rational is the X axis has the least mass and is, therefore, more accurate in resolving the thickness  or "greyscale" of the lithophane.

title: Star Bracelet
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
MEANT FOR TPU FILAMENT !!

I've been using Ninjaflex for my test prints and final; 85A shore rating.
Inner radius is roughly 5.5 inches when fully closed, can be close to 7 inches before the inner ridges don't grab very well.
Was designed for a 2 year old in mind, and those little buggers grow fast, haha.

The outside of the band is hollow, so the stars can compress in and be played with.

The supports are a little thin, but print just fine in this version. I'll upload a version with some thicker supports in a few days.

For other Houdini artists doing modeling, I'll release my support generation tool I created for this. Wont be until tuesday/wednesday.
Just give it a group of primitives and a base object to use as your print bed, and it will go from there.

I'm sorry about the non-commercial share alike, I'm considering expanding this type of bracelet design into many designs in the future. So I don't know where this will take me.
That being said, design suggestions will be listened to!

Printer:

Tevo Tarantula

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1 or .15

Infill:

No gaps

Notes:

When I say raft, I've been printing with 11+ brim line count.
The supports are thin, so you must print with a brim!
Standard working TPU settings should be fine here.

225-235 C hot end.
12.5-15mm/s speeds for everything
10-20% skin and infill overlap
I've been printing 105% extrusion
>=45 degree touching bed supports; specifically for the band

Since this is a semi-closed tube, I'd suggest putting some pauses in your gcode or manually pause the print to do clean ups with some snips/scissors to make final clean up easier for you.
For final touches, you can use a soldering iron / wood brander/burning tool to smooth out any filament extrudes that get caught mid print.

Since the bracelet is lifted off the bed with a support ring object under it, it should be a little more forgiving to getting it off the bed without stabbing the main bracelet itself.
Just make sure you cut the bottom ring off after you are done print!

For the stars, hopefully there wont be too many interconnecting lines between the main bracelet and the support. But be careful when cutting the support off of the stars. They are tiny!

title: Ikea Table Filament Through Tube
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
When creating my enclosure for my printer, I found I needed more space for the filament spools. To this end I created the Spool Holder End Stops for 1/2 PVC pipe so that I could mount the spools to the upper part of the enclosure. My enclosure is made from multiple Ikea 20" square tables stacked and bolted together. To that end I found when boring a hole in them it had edges that really could not be rounded due to the materials used, so instead I created this little guy that could slide through and be secured creating a smooth entrance between layers. I personally use this guy to allow the spool to feed the printer from above with out letting a massive amount of the warm air to escape the print area into the upper chamber. I suspect such a simple thing could be used for other purposes as well such as wire bundles leaving such a DIY enclosure or even on a desk with similar dimensions.

I personally found this print to work best in PLA+ due to the need for maintaining the dimensions as snug as possible, though I suspect it could be improved by more expensive materials that I am not willing to use for such a simple part.

description.text:
As I kept modifying my i3, I've reached the point where I am satisfied with this X axis.  
Just print all the parts with layer height equal or lower than 0.3mm and extrusion width 0.5mm or lower.  
These parts are made so the bearings/bushings are fixed with zip ties.  
It can be a little tricky to put the zip ties in the holes. The way I do it is by bending the point of the tie so it looks like a J, like a hook.  
If you have problems fixing the nut, use a soldering iron on it until it aligns with the hole.  
The tensioner is made so two 624 or F624 bearings fit side by side.

remixed_from.title: Recycled CD Cases: Doll's House // Toy Shelves

description.text: This is a remix of the Recycled CD Cases Dollhouse. I made the parts sturdier and print them in nylon, which is strong and a little flexible. It is tough enough to survive my 2-yr old. There are more photos of the finished product on my blog.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15-mm layers

Infill:

100%

Notes:

I printed with Taulman Bridge nylon. I did not test with other materials, although I think ABS might work OK. I used 5-mm brim to keep from warping.

Print the following:
8 corners
8 tees
2 straights
2 crosses
2 crosses - 60 degree left leg
2 crosses - 60 degree right leg

Assemble with 15 CD cases with custom inserts (floors and walls).
Leave the outside walls and roof completely clear to see inside.
Populate with your favorite doll-sized toys and enjoy!

I was a little worried my 2-yr old would be too rough on the original design, so I beefed it up with thicker 2-mm walls. I also added a recess for the trim feature on the CD case edges to snap into and added a little gripper bump out at the end of the legs. I printed this in nylon so it would be strong and flexible. The pieces slide or snap over the cases. I neglected to cut out the gripper bump and walls where the trim features of adjoining cases protrude. This causes a little deformation and can lead to delamination at the joints if not installed with care. I feel the pieces are almost stronger than the CD cases themselves. Assembling the dollhouse is a little different than the original design because these pieces should slide on the cases from the ends. Thus, one must build up floors and install them from the ground up: floor, walls, floor, walls, roof.

If you want to hack on this, here is the Fusion 360 model. Or, download the Fusion archive .f3d file.

description.text:
These are inserts that can be placed into the voids of the rear motor/transmission mount on a MkV GTI/Jetta (and similar era Audi). They come in two pieces, one for the forward voids and another for the rear. They slip in easily enough but will need some sort of plate/disk to help hold them in place. Otherwise, they will just fall out when staring the engine. Similar commercial versions of the insert include a metal disk but I just made my own from some think metal sheeting I had. I'll try to get a picture of them actually installed later.

Vibrations are only noticeable on startup, not during driving or idle.

I made the front insert (black in the photo) out of some carbon fiber nylon I had from a sample. Didn't have enough for both pieces so I used PETG for the rear (green in the picture). Didn't worry about heat but did want a material that had a bit of flex to cut down on NVH. Haven't had them installed long to see how long they last but I did notice an improvement in power delivery since the engine wasn't moving as much.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2mm

Infill:

30

Notes:

There is a lip around each piece. I oriented them so they had the wide portion towards the top (like a "U") instead of how they are pictured so the layer lines will be oriented best for the forces they would be expected to encounter. So no supports were needed I manually dropped the bottom "lip" to below the build plate. Hopefully, you can see what I meant by the picture.
Took a picture of the rear mount and imported it into a drawing program where I could trace some paths of the voids. Then imported into Fusion 360 and extruded them out.

comments.text: Good concept for learning how to make 3D models, but stop wasting your time and use Powerflex inserts the ones made of some polyurethane stuff which can actually flex.
comments.author: aqibi2000

comments.text: I've had poly inserts on previous cars and really liked them but some just added too much NVH for this implementation (my wife's car). I'd just replaced the engine and trans mounts and noticed that the rear rubber mount had what looked like a small tear starting. I just wanted to stabilize it, not really add a "performance" improvement. Plus, replacing the mount would require dropping the subframe (or whatever VW calls it) and pressing it out, not something I wanted to tackle at this time. It had the desired effect, reducing the engine torquing in place and helping get the power down a bit better.
comments.author: aqibi2000

comments.text: You have actually completed misinterpreted what I’ve written.
comments.author: rt4me

comments.text: Oh no, I'm familiar with the Powerflex, Neuspeed and other inserts for the car (poly and aluminum) but they would probably add more vibration than my wife would want. Besides, I like 50 cents in material and same day install rather $20-40 for the inserts and waiting for delivery. :)
comments.author: aqibi2000

description.text: I created this Barbie furniture using Microsoft's 3D builder. The set includes a couch, chair and ottoman. My daughter combines the chair and ottoman to make a bed for her doll "guests". I use a Mod-T Printer so the model is approximately 100 mm wide.

Printer:

Mod-T

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Yes

Notes:

I am using basic settings.

After loads of changes, tweaks, and fixes I've decided to give this project an official name. It is now called the Rex/P Ergonomic Centurion System or R.E.C.S. There will be additions in the future, but it's come far enough along now for official release. The design goal was always minimalist, ergonomic, useful, and awesome looking, and I feel that has been achieved.

I've added a quad rail system for the Rex Rifle. I have completely started over from scratch and built a new model.

Inspired by the work of others but having desired and even built a few from wood years before I ever started 3D modelling, I thought it time to build a model. I started in Fusion 360 using what I have learned (yay conduit box tutorial), and a few things I did in Tinkercad (symmetric copying and joining two models).

print_settings.Notes:: Make sure to check out peetersm's original work to print out a gauge that will help you determine layer height and number of layers.

description.text:
I moved the hole a small amount (so the light isn't right up against the back of the lithophane as much), increased the max # of layers, and added ability to add some text on the back (e.g., name, date). It works best with just a little of text--I wouldn't try to put an essay on there as the text isn't really curved around the sphere so much as projected on it. This is my first share-worthy remix so I hope you like it :)

Tips, credit, etc. should go to the original author, peetersm, for this creative use of lithophanes. I printed one for myself and several family members and it was a huge hit!

** note: although I updated the scad file to use 150 pixel resolution, I haven't printed this yet.

Also uploaded GCode.

I recommend printing it at 0.2

Update:

I was stupid and I didn't leave the room for rail, also some of the holes were off. I Had manually got rid of piece to allow to fit around rail, and have created holes for the screws. now fits perfectly and airflow is perfect. I went and updated model with new holes and added some extra just in case as well as room for rail.

Hopefully no one printed bad model yet and wasted filament.

Sorry guys. Trail and error until perfection.

Hopefully this is it. I needed good fan duct for a long time.

description.text: I designed this for a friend who wanted to keep her existing case and AIO from her Alienware Aurora R4 but wanted to upgrade to an 8600k and a z370 motherboard. This will work for any Corsair AIO with the screws integrated into the retention ring (Ex. H110i).

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.06

Infill:

80%

Notes:

Over 80% infill on my printer would increase the dimensions of the screw threads to a point to where they wouldn't work.

Prime by screwing screws into tester to see if they are printed well enough, and to wear down threads a bit. Do the same to the backplate and then install.

If after priming if the top of the screw breaks off when screwing in the retention ring, increase printing temperature and then print again.

Has been in use for ~2 months at this point with no issues and stellar temperatures.

comments.text: Looking good. I am still getting some slight banding at 0.1mm. If I move Z up or down at a medium rate I can see wobble, but it must be only slightly interfering with the bed to cause the banding.  Hoping that a rigid coupler might clear that up but can't seem to find a rigid 5-8mm so I might get someone local to machine one.  The top of the rear hex screw is literally less than 1mm from the y axis, but not touching. Seems okay at this point.  This ballscrew is large due to using such large bearings, I think it is possible that the screws holding on the extruder motor fan could interfere with it if you printed a large, somewhat tall object.  I should probably replace these with something more flush with the fan.  All in all I'm pleased with the mod.  Everything moves very smoothly.

title: Adjustable Cooling fan, grill, cover. Air flow limiter. CTC

description.text:
With the CTC machine only have an off/on cooling fan and other mods damaging the main board, I thought I would approach this problem differently as some materials require less than 100% cooling. This fan shroud simply slips over any 40mm fan frame, you limit the amount of air the fan can pull, therefore ranging the cooling effect by turning the cover, opening more or less of an opening. If you require 100% simply pull the shroud off.

Warning. Using the fan with the cover completely closed can cause the fan to work harder than usual and cause damage to the fan or main board. If you do don't require cooling turn the fan off. I accept no liability for any damage you cause to your machine.

author: yonchicat

title: Power Switch Case for Anet A8

description.text:
This is a basic power switch case for the Anet A8 3D printer. It can be screwed into a corner of the frame of the printer.

Some notes:

  • You will have to drill holes through the frame of the printer and through the printed case in order to insert mounting screws. It can be difficult to drill through the acrylic frame, which is very durable and slippery. The mounting screws I used were the same ones that came with the printer.
  • There are two holes in the bottom of the case for cable entry/exit.
  • There is a hole in the side for a toggle switch. You might want to adjust the size of this hole depending on the switch you are using. I had to drill mine out a little bit. Choose a switch that is rated for at least 120V. Not sure on the amperage.
  • The hot wire (black or brown) should pass through the switch. The other wires, neutral and ground, can be connected with wire nuts or soldered together. Cover exposed solder joints with heatshrink.
  • Consider which way you want the switch to be facing (up or down) when the machine is powered. Convention would dictate that the machine turns on when the switch is pressed up, and off when it is pressed down.

description.text:
This is a plant holder. The idea is to create a wall of plants on the back of an acrylic aquarium. As most acrylic aquariums have an opening in the back that is about 2" wide, this was designed to fit in that back space. It is only about 3-4" tall though. Ideally this would be much larger, but this was the first try.

This was printed through 3dhubs.com and came out pretty nice. This design is a bit smaller for the wall part and bigger for the back hanger, so expect an update.

I had another piece printed and used nylon yarn to attach the two parts together. The bottom half in the blurry picture is that piece. Using nylon string, Java fern can be attached to the holder to grow. Other plants, like java moss would also work, and even floating plants could be anchored to this holder.

I wanted to design a mohawk for my Vorpal Hexapod. I decided that it would look better if the top of the cap was round, so I started by modifying the cap. Initially I designed the short mohawk then I decided to design a taller mohawk as well.

Afterward I realized that people may want to print them for the standard Vorpal cap they are already using so I modified both designs. In total there are 4 mohawks (short and tall ones for both modified and standard caps). I've also included here the model of the modified cap that I printed.

The CAD pictures are of the mohawk design for the standard cap. The pictures of the actual hexapod are all of the modified cap design (the short mohawk is in purple and the tall mohawk is a red/yellow combo).

The mohawks have a slot in the back for the standard Vorpal magnet which aligns with the magnet in the back of the cap. However, I've slightly flexed both mohawks to get them onto the tabs for the modified cap and they stay on rigidly by themselves without a magnet. I suspect the mohawks for the standard cap will squeeze the top of the cap and stay on in the same manner (please provide feedback if you try them).

I also designed my own aggressive eyes which are on the hexapod in all the pictures. If you're interested they can be found here: thingiverse.com/thing:2743717

Enjoy and if you print one please post a make/picture!

description.text:
There are 3 types of strainers modeled:
1 - 5x5mm grid
2 - 2x2mm grid
3 - No Grid, with a 3mm lip. This one is to allow you to glue on SS mesh that suits your needs.

The strainers have a 15mm BSP Thread on the end to be used with a 15mm female bulkhead. I use these on my tanks:
(https://www.bunnings.com.au/garden-rain-15mm-female-tank-access-outlet_p3113666)

These are designed for aquariums but could be used anywhere needed I guess. I use 5x5mm grid for larger adult fish (i..e Apistogrammas), 2x2mm grid for smaller adult fish (i.e. Celestial Pearl Danios), and the No Grid version I glue on a super fine SS mesh which I use in fry tanks.

Note - I printed at 0.2mm resolution for hte bottom half, and 0.1mm resolution for the threads because my printer doesnt print threads well at 0.2mm. I did this using Simplify 3D variable settings wizard.

title: Creality CR-10 E3D Titan mount Remix for smaller steppers

description.text:
Lucashayes design was perfect but when I printed it, I didn't consider my updated stepper was a pancake (smaller ), half size, whatever!!! So I used my stock stepper instead. So I quickly modified his (I've completely made a new one as well, but this was purely, a take his modify it to hold the smaller stepper and print it. Boom.

All the work was done by Lucashayes and I appreciate him having something ready for my to get my Titan installed on my CR-10.

01/10/2018:
Changed the model a bit , beefed it up in areas and made sure things aligned better. The previous one caused a bit of misalignment and the titan didn't want to mount without tweaking it.

This one is completely new, based on Lucashayes design and taking the specs from my pancake motor

Added a square hole at the top to help with cooling, also probably saves some print time.
Designed it 100% in fusion 360

author: Kippers

description.text:
See the full instructions here.
http://www.instructables.com/id/Split-Grommet-for-Dishwasher-Aqua-stop-Hose/

I have just built a new kitchen and when I went to fit the dishwasher it had this enormous valve on the end of the hose. It called an Aqua-stop and its suppose to stop your house from flooding if the hose should come off your dishwasher or washing machine.

The Problem is, the hose has to go through the cabinet but I didn't want to cut a huge hole in the bottom of my new cabinet.
I look on the internet.... No help there. I asked a plumber, he didn't know what I was talking about. So After a bit of thinking, this is what I came up with this.
Just print off the grommet (I did it in black as I run out of white filament) Use a 75mm hole saw to cut a hole in the cabinet, hook up your hoses and fit the grommet.The sides of the hole push Up against the grommet and ensure a tight fit.

Job done. Looks tidy and there is no gaping hole around my hoses.

This is a randomizable and customizable cellular automaton snowflake generator in BlocksCAD. It comes in two versions, a 20-level version (board radius up to 20) and a 40-level version. The 40-level version is just barely within the limits of BlocksCAD abilities: BlocksCAD becomes sluggish but it still works (I recommend using Firefox instead of Chrome for much better responsiveness).

A more realistic simulation is here.

The automaton puts down a live (colored) hex at the middle of the board, and then follows evolution rules (like in Conway's Game of Life). The default rule set (darker blue screenshots) is Stephen Wolfram's: a live cell survives forever, and a new cell generates when it has exactly one live neighbor.

You can vary the rule set by varying what effect different numbers of live neighbors (0-6) have on survival or generation. You can also set indeterministic rules, where there are probabilities between 0 and 1 of survival or generation in the different neighbor count cases. In indeterministic cases, snowflake symmetry (six fold rotational, plus reflection) is still enforced by the code.

The light blue images were made with an indeterministic rule set where the only change made was to set the probability of generation when there is one neighbor to 0.5, so the generation parameters were 0,0.5,0,0,0,0,0. These images look more snowflake-like to me. Another interesting set of generation parameters is 0,0.5,0,0.1,0,0,1 (0.5 chance of generation with one neighbor; 0.1 chance with 3 neighbors, certainty with 6 neighbors).

You can post in comments what are some interesting rule sets. The default rule and its above probabilistic variant are quite printable. Rules where all the survival probabilities are 1 will result in completely connected snowflakes. If some survival probabilities are less than 1, there may be outliers.

The OpenSCAD-based Customizer was generated by exporting OpenSCAD code from BlocksCAD, and moving the variable definitions to the top of the file for Customizer compatibility.

If you turn on color shading (by having different color1 and color2 settings), the color shading goes by the step during which a cell was generated. You can also turn on periodic banding for a special color effect.

It was difficult to implement a cellular automaton in BlocksCAD since BlocksCAD does not support arrays and, for further complication, is a functional language.

To speed up the code, the cellular automaton is only implemented on a 1/12 segment of the board, with the rest reconstructed by symmetry.

The heart of the code is a giant recursive evolve module that (in the radius 40 version) takes 421 arguments. The first argument counts iterations. The remaining 420 arguments each store one cell of data. If the the iteration count reaches 0, then evolve calls draw(i,j,v) for each cell. It has to do this by a union of 420 invocation, since there are no arrays and hence no way of iterating over the arguments. The draw(i,j,v) function draws the hex if v is non-zero, as well as drawing the up to 11 other hexes that are related to it by the snowflake symmetries.

Next, the evolve module recursively calls itself with the iteration count decremented, and each cell argument evolved. The evolution of the cell arguments is done by adding up the neighbor counts for each argument checking to see if the cell should be alive. There is a hard-coded call to a cell evolution function for every single one of the 420 arguments.

There is also a go module that calls evolve with its 421 (radius 40 version) initial arguments: an iterations count, follows by a central 1, followed by zeroes. Finally, the code linearly extrudes the output of the go module to make it 3D.

At this point you might think I was crazy to drag-and-drop evolution code for every one of 420 cells in evolve. Well, I didn't. I wrote a quick-and-dirty python script (included as blockscad.py and cell6.py: the latter is the main script) which can generate a subset of BlocksCAD xml code, and used it to automatically generates the giant evolve module that calls cell for each cell, and the big go module.

The rest of the code was manually entered in BlocksCAD: the go module, some top-level code, the cell evolution function, and the draw module.

Assembling all the code in BlocksCAD was a bit of work. Most of the manually entered code was saved to xml as a backup (included as the "hand code"). Then I imported the xml file generated by python into BlocksCAD. Then I added the extrusion wrapper around the go module. (Or at least that's how I did it when I finally figured out how to make it work.) I then made some optimizations.

https://youtu.be/sJjrz4mL5aA

This remake adds new software and hardware to gwfong's Googly Eyes Minion Clock remake (https://www.instructables.com/id/Googly-Eyes-Minion-Clock/) based on Minion Dave by Poh (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:403110).

I have created a PCB that holds a ULN2803A octal darlington transistor array to drive the two stepper motors. It also contains a DS1302 real time clock chip, its crystal and battery. It is driven by an Arduino Pro Mini. The Eagle files are included. I used the toner method to create the board.

The software supports two buttons.

  • The MIDNIGHT button is used to tell the software where the 12 O'clock position is. You can rotate the eyes with your fingers and press this button when the eyeballs are in the correct location.
  • The MODE button switches between clock mode and one of four random animations.

The RTC needs to be set via the Arduino IDE Serial Monitor when the FTDI programmer is present. Just sent the date and time in the form yyyy,MM,dd,hh,mm,ss and the software will program the RTC.

I sourced my parts from eBay and they are all easily obtainable. I got the DS1302, crystal and battery holder from a cheap RTC board (https://www.ebay.com/itm/DS1302-Clock-Module-Real-Time-Clock-Module-for-arduino-without-Battery-CA-NEW/141976854631?hash=item210e7ae067:g:B60AAOxyDo1TjwO9). The only 25mm stepper motors I could find were from eBay (https://www.ebay.com/itm/1pcs-For-NMB-DC5V-15-25mm-4-Phase-5-Wire-Step-Stepping-Stepper-Motor-With-Gear/231225110024?hash=item35d6172e08:g:T4UAAOxyThVTabLK).
These motors are fragile and have very poor resolution. They have 24 steps per revolution making the minute hand move 2.5 minutes on each step. Also, because they have no gearing, they don't have much torque. The software can accommodate higher resolution stepper motors. If anyone ever does modify this design to use 28BYJ-48 stepper motors for example, you can change the defines at the start of the code. You may need to reduce the RPM speed for higher resolution stepper motors.

PS: If any of you design experts do redesign this to take 28BYJ-48 stepper motors, my suggestion to you would be to mount them near the back and put the eyeballs on long shafts.

print_settings.Infill:: 20% for the tires, 10% for the car.

description.text:
Newton101 designed a really cute toy car, I printed it out and it had very sharp edges, the pegs of the tires broke off easily, and the wheels are a chocking haszard, they were 23mm in diameter which is 0.9" and in the U.S. the choking hazard diameter is anything under 1.25" (31.75mm).
I didn't want to give it to my daughter cause I know she would break the wheels off and if she hit someone/fell on it the edges could cause injury so I widened the body a little so that I could use 12mm M4 screws to make sure they stayed in, smoothed out the body, rounded all the corners, then for the wheels I made them 40mm in diameter and instead of fragile pins they are held onto the body with 4 M4 12mm screws and it is a very tight fit on the body so they are never coming out without a hex wrench.
Thank you Newton101 for the awesome design, I just tweaked it a bit so I felt good about giving it to my daughter.
I may add the headlights back in another version but I need to get this printing for a Christmas present and they got in the way of rounding it.

Printer:

Anycubic Linear Plus

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20% for the tires, 10% for the car.

Notes:

I ended up going with 20% infill for the tires not to make them stronger but to give the edges of the tires more something to hold it flat so they quit curling and snagging the print head.
also printing the tires slower (40mms instead of my normal 80) really helped the curling up of the edge of the tires, even with good cooling it was happening, after 4 failed attempts I slowed the print down and upped the infill a little and they printed beautifully.

description.text:
This is a tiny planetary gearbox (not my design). See original page for details. When you inevitably fail to print the little bolts and/or they break really easily, try BoltModified.stl. It'll print a threaded rod on its side, making it much stronger. There is no bolt head, cut with scissors or wire clippers to size. You may need to print more than one depending on which gear kit you're going with.

And when the annoying pins on the carrier inevitably pop off, try CarrierModified.stl. Instead of printing the pins, it has holes so you can add your own (of a suitably strong material).

These are my Emergency Christmas Modifications.

Though they may sound like a form of gymnastics the Parametric Rings are simply ordinary loops you may print in colour. You can change settings in the Parametric_Rings OpenSCAD file to set the diameter of the rings, and to choose from some optional extra supports. You may need to use the supports when printing large diameter rings as they tend to warp and/or lift from the bed. You can export single rings to be printed in the suggested colours or you can export a full set and print it in a single colour. A short video of one possible way of assembling the rings can be viewed at: http://yuleblinker.com/parametric-rings/ The ideal colours to use can all be found as part of the Rainbow Fun Pack available from http://www.faberdashery.co.uk/products-page/print-materials/rainbow-fun-pack/. (I am not associated with Faberdashery at all but often use their plastics). The suggested colours to use are:
Electric Blue, Mellow Yellow, Classic Black, Village Green and Fire Truck Red. You can print a single ring at about 60mm diameter easily with each colour from the Rainbow Fun Pack.

Creating the ring models:
  • 1) Open the Parametric_Rings.scad file.
  • 2) Enter a value for the Ring_Radius
  • 3) if you choose a diameter above 50mm you may want to consider using one of the 'support' options: use_gap_support will add a thin layer of material that spans any gaps - useful for medium size rings. use_mouse_ears adds small circles of material around the ring to help keep it stuck to the bed when printing - useful for large rings.
  • 4) Uncomment the line for the model you'd like to create. Options are: Linked_Rings (try it and see!), All_Rings_Solid (to print all in single colour), All_Rings_Bed (to print all rings in single colour for later assembly), Blue_Ring_Solo, Black_Ring_Solo, Red_Ring_Solo, Yellow_Ring_Solo and Green_Ring_Solo (creates model of single ring)
    • Printing the rings
    If you choose to print large rings (anything above about 50mm) then you may find it a challenge to get them to stick to the printer bed. The stresses set up as the plastic cools tends to make the rings warp and lift off the bed - experiment with the different support structures included in the OpenSCAD file. I found the 'mouse-ears' worked well for 70mm rings.
    The first and second picture shows a blue ring with 'mouse-ear' supports. In the second picture the support material is being removed.
  • 1) Print off a set of rings in a single colour or each ring in a different colour
  • 2) Trim off any support structures you may have printed with a sharp craft knife.
  • 3) Assemble and enjoy!
    • If you need some help figuring out how the rings can be assembled then look at the OpenSCAD file with the Linked_Rings option uncommented and hit F5.

comments.author: Alzibiff

title: E3D Mount for Pittsburgh (Harbor Freight) Digital Indicator

description.text:
I had two issues with the original. First, the hole for the indicator was too small, so I changed it. Also, I didn't want to heat up an M4 bolt when I have a set of metric taps. So I made the set screw holes much smaller and then did a drill and tap for the holes. By the way, Harbor Freight has the Drill Master bits that are a drill bit up front, a tap in the middle and deburr face at the end. These work pretty well on 3D printed items. Just make a pilot hole smaller than you want and drill it out with the tap. Of course, it is still plastic, so it isn't going to make as good of a connection as a properly threaded piece of metal, but for this purpose it was fine.

In addition, the Pittsburgh has a giant hook in the back that gets in the way of everything. So I took off the back, measured the back, and made a new one. Lost a screw. Found a screw. I didn't bother countersinking the holes or beveling the edge because with this mount it doesn't matter.

In practice, get one part of your bed level how you like it. Snap this on so that the probe is lower than your nozzle and zero it. Now move to the other corners and make them read zero also. Poof! Bed is level (well, trammed, but everyone says level).

Since I have E3Ds on two of my 3 printers (and soon to be on all), this is pretty portable. By the way, this is two separate pieces, so if you just want the back you don't have to take the mount.

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/kHYoUpiU2Ep

Belt tensioner.
It will accept up to a 7.5mm width belt.

You will also need a 3mm screw and nut.

I printed at .2 mm layer height and 100% infill.

1) Insert the nut in the recess inside the body.
2) Thread a nut from the otherside through the nut.
3) Put the tensioner inside the body.
4) Thread belt through assembly.
Make sure the tensioner doesn't hit or interfere with anything.
5) Tighten screw to tighten belt.

This will way over tighten your belt if your not careful.

If it's way over tight your belts will vibrate REALLY REALLY messing with your prints. Ya, guess how I figured that out....

The Mrs. wanted a small TV in the bedroom. We have fairly limited space, so a stand/table wasn't an option. I could have bought a mount for a reasonable cost, but I don't own a 3D printer to go and buy stuff that I can make!

This is a wall mount for a VESA 100mm x 100mm hole pattern. The TV I have mounted on this system weighs ~15lbs (6.8kg).

I used a brim/raft on these parts to make it a little easier to remove the pieces at the end of the print. It isn't necessary, I just prefer to have a bit of a lip to get under the part to keep from damaging the corners.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15mm

Infill:

Variable

Notes:

TV Bracket:

-Print Resolution: 0.15mm
-Infill: 50% or greater is recommended, but as low as 30% could be sufficient depending on the weight of your screen.
-Material: PLA 1.75mm
-Extruder Temp: 210°C
-Bed Temp: 55°C
-Hardware needed: (4) M4 bolts. Length is dependent on monitor. I used 20mm allen head bolts. I made the part to allow for a variety of fastener head sizes/shapes.

Wall Bracket:

-Print Resolution: 0.15mm
-Infill: 50% or greater is recommended, but as low as 30% could be sufficient depending on the weight of your screen.
-Material: PLA 1.75mm
-Extruder Temp: 210°C
-Bed Temp: 55°C
-Hardware needed: (6) #8 screws. Align the left or right with a stud. Use hollow wall anchors on the other side if necessary.

Finshing

I had to take some 220 grit sandpaper to the edges of the sliding dovetail on both pieces in order to allow for a better fit. I made very little to no tolerance between the pieces. I would rather do some light sanding/trimming than to have parts that are too loose. A rubber mallet, a block of wood, and some light tapping can help it the fitting process.

description.text:
This is a pack of 1:100 E Series vehicles

Late by 2 hours...... damn....... anyway Merry Christmas!!! I can't thank you guys enough for your support. here's to another year of good models and new modelers!!!

Currently contains

E-5
E-10
E-25
E-50
Flakpanzer E-50
E-75
Sturmgeschütz E-75
E-100
Sturmgeschütz E-100
Flakpanzer E-100
Heavy Missile Launcher E-100

I poured through dozens of historic texts and academic papers to determine which of these vehicles are in-fact real designs. I could confirm every vehicle except for the flakpanzer E-100, Heavy Missile Launcher E-100, and the late turret on the E-50. I have doubts that any of these 3 are real WW2 German designs but it's fine.

All vehicles made from scratch

Please join my group http://www.thingiverse.com/groups/the-world-at-war/topics

Please view my other packs https://www.thingiverse.com/TigerAce1945/designs

remixed_from.title: Mushroom Grinder (with Catchment and Storage areas)

description.text: Printed @ 100% infill and with 7 to 10 percent supports. Used small hinge design by Robhumm https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:21444 and that is printed at same settings @ 100 percent scale. Same scale as the box basically. The orange one is printed @ 100% scale and the grinder fits pretty good but without bottom bracket. The Glow in the dark one(white) was printed @ 102% scale, and the bracket fits the grinder pretty well, the grinder doesnt fit the 100% scale box. Please excuse the peices in the middle of the bracket, I am trying to design a rising platform so the mushroom rises when you open the box, but it is taking too much time to perfect, so I figured I would release part of it so the grinder can sit in it. I will be updating eventually with a newer design but this one works well. Also the hinges are glued to the box starting with the lid (thats what i did at least). The part of the hinge with one loop as opposed to two is glued to the lid. It is the smaller side when looking from the side of the hinge. Should be glued right on each corner of the lid and should be flush with the top and side of the lid. Hope you guys enjoy! My first design for thingiverse....No design experience, just going off of will and instincts :)

Maybe fit a different tool as well. I got me here made Ã¢ÂÂÃ¢ÂÂa complete system for tool holder. I do not like when the tool is loose in the case. So now I have a separate holder for each tool creates. This holder can be screwed onto a plywood board now. (Spax 3 mm). Holes for the screws are integrated.
